-------------XAMPP--------------------------
============================================
üü¢ 1. Set MySQL Root Password

By default, MySQL in XAMPP has no password for the root user.

Steps:

Start Apache and MySQL in the XAMPP Control Panel.

Open your browser and go to:

http://localhost/phpmyadmin/


Click on the ‚ÄúUser accounts‚Äù tab.

Find the root user (usually listed as root@localhost).

Click ‚ÄúEdit privileges‚Äù ‚Üí scroll down to ‚ÄúChange password‚Äù section.

Enter your new password and click ‚ÄúGo‚Äù.

Alternatively (via command line):

Open the XAMPP Shell (click the ‚ÄúShell‚Äù button in XAMPP Control Panel).

Run the following commands:

mysql -u root


Then:

ALTER USER 'root'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'YourNewPassword';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;

üü° 2. Update phpMyAdmin Configuration

After setting the MySQL password, phpMyAdmin will need it to log in.

Steps:

Open this file in a text editor:

C:\xampp\phpMyAdmin\config.inc.php


Find this line:

$cfg['Servers'][$i]['auth_type'] = 'config';
$cfg['Servers'][$i]['user'] = 'root';
$cfg['Servers'][$i]['password'] = '';


Replace it with:

$cfg['Servers'][$i]['password'] = 'YourNewPassword';


(Optional but safer) Change auth type to cookie:

$cfg['Servers'][$i]['auth_type'] = 'cookie';


‚Üí This will prompt you to log in manually each time you access phpMyAdmin.
